Second, industry participation feeds back into the research agenda. Problems that are easy to benchmark, commercially valuable, and compatible with existing data infrastructures receive disproportionate investment. Fields with weaker data standardization or less obvious monetization may lag even if their social value is high. This suggests that public funding and research policy remain necessary to avoid an overly market-shaped definition of scientific importance.

The competitive landscape is therefore hybrid. Open science remains essential for validation and diffusion, yet frontier models increasingly depend on proprietary compute and industrial-scale engineering. A likely medium-term outcome is a layered ecosystem: open methods and benchmarks at the academic core, with industrial players dominating the most compute-intensive and operationally integrated systems.

\section{Challenges, Risks, and Limitations}
Despite rapid progress, the deployment of AI in scientific research faces structural limits.

