AI has moved from a specialized computational technique to a strategic research infrastructure for modern science. Large-scale learning systems now support pattern recognition in massive datasets, surrogate modeling for expensive simulations, extraction of latent structure from unstructured literature, and the control of robotic experimentation platforms. This shift matters because many scientific bottlenecks are informational rather than purely conceptual: relevant data are fragmented, experiments are costly, and the search spaces for molecules, materials, and models are combinatorially vast. In such settings, AI can reduce search cost, improve predictive accuracy, and help scientists prioritize scarce experimental attention.

