The most important contribution of AI to science is not simply higher predictive accuracy in isolated tasks. It is the reconfiguration of the research workflow. AI can compress multiple stages of scientific work: it helps formulate candidate hypotheses, score them with predictive models, choose experiments adaptively, and integrate results into updated models. In effect, it increases the rate at which a research program can move around a hypothesis space.

