These paradigms matter because they change where scarcity lies. In classical science, scarcity often centered on human analysis and hand-crafted models. In AI-enabled science, scarcity shifts toward high-quality labeled data, experimental throughput, trustworthy benchmarks, and compute access. That shift has strategic implications for universities, national laboratories, and firms. The ability to maintain data pipelines, instrumentation, and model infrastructure increasingly shapes scientific competitiveness.

\section{Industry Trends and Economic Implications}
AI for science is now an industrial as well as academic phenomenon. Pharmaceutical companies use machine learning across target identification, medicinal chemistry, and trial design; materials and semiconductor firms use AI to optimize discovery and manufacturing; cloud providers treat scientific AI as a demand driver for high-performance computing services. This industrialization is important for two reasons.

First, it changes the innovation pipeline. Companies can internalize large portions of the discovery stack by combining proprietary datasets, domain experts, and compute resources. This may accelerate translation from research to product, especially in drug discovery and advanced materials. But it also risks concentrating scientific capability in a small set of organizations with unusual access to capital, data, and specialized hardware.

Second, industry participation feeds back into the research agenda. Problems that are easy to benchmark, commercially valuable, and compatible with existing data infrastructures receive disproportionate investment. Fields with weaker data standardization or less obvious monetization may lag even if their social value is high. This suggests that public funding and research policy remain necessary to avoid an overly market-shaped definition of scientific importance.

